      <main id="main-doc">
          <section class="main-section" id="Summary">
            <header>Summary</header>
            <article>
              <p>Crohn's Disease is an Inflammatory Bowel Disease.</p>
              <p>It's a disease that causes inflammation in the digestive tract.</p>
            </article>
          </section>
          <section class="main-section" id="Who's_at_Risk">
            <header>Who's at Risk</header>
            <article>
              <p>The cause is unknown.</p>
              <p>Risk Factors include:</p>
              <ul class="ul1">
                <li>Family History</li>
                <li>Smoking
                  <code>Risk*2</code>
                </li>
                <li>Certain Medications:
                  <ul class="ul2">
                    <li>Antibiotics</li>
                    <li>Birth Control pills</li>
                    <li>NSAIDs</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>High-fat Diet</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </section>
          <section class="main-section"id="Diagnosis">
            <header>Diagnosis</header>
            <article>
              <p>A medical history, which includes asking about your symptoms</p>
              <p>A family history</p>
              <p>A physical exam, including:</p>
              <ul class="ul1">
                <li>Checking for bloating in your abdomen</li>
                <li>Listening to sounds within your abdomen using a stethoscope
</li>
                <li>Tapping on your abdomen to check for tenderness and pain and to see if your liver or spleen is abnormal or enlarged</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Various tests, including:</p>
                <ul class="ul1">
                  <li>Blood and stool tests
                    <ul class="ul2">
                      <li>Bacteria Culture Test</li>
                      <li>C-Reactive Protein (CRP) Test
                        <code>Normal<0.3mg/dL</code>
                      </li>
                      <li>Lower GI Series (Barium Enema)</li>
                      <li>White Blood Cell (WBC) in Stool
                        <code>Normal=4.5 to 11.0*10g/L</code>
                      </li>
                      <li>Xylose Testing
                        <code>Normal>25mg/dL</code>
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>
                  <li>A colonoscopy</li>
                  <li>An upper GI endoscopy</li>
                  <li>Diagnostic imaging tests, such as a CT scan or an upper GI series</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
          </section>
          <section class="main-section" id="Symptoms">
            <header>Symptoms</header>
            <article>
              <p>Symptoms include:</p>
              <ul class="ul1">
                <li>Diarrhea</li>
                <li>Cramping and pain in your abdomen
</li>
                <li>Weight loss
</li>
                <li>Anemia
                  <code>Hemoglobin<14g/dL</code>
                </li>
                <li>Eye redness or pain
</li>
                <li>Fatigue</li>
                <li>Fever</li>
                <li>Joint pain or soreness
</li>
                <li>Nausea or loss of appetite
</li>
                <li>Skin changes that involve red, tender bumps under the skin
</li>
                <li>Intestinal obstruction, 
</li>
                <li>Fistulas</li>
                <li>Abscesses</li>
                <li>Anal fissures, 
</li>
                <li>Ulcers</li>
                <li>Malnutrition</li>
                <li>Inflammation in other areas of your body, such as your joints, eyes, and skin
</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </section>
          <section class="main-section" id="Treatment">
            <header>Treatment</header>
            <article>
              <p>There is no cure for Crohn's Disease.</p>
              <p>Medications:</p>
              <ul class="ul1">
                <li>Aminosalicylates:
                  <ul class="ul2">
                    <li>balsalazide</li>
                    <li>mesalamine</li>
                    <li>olsalazine</li>
                    <li>Sulfasalazine</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Corticosteroids:
                  <ul class="ul2">
                    <li>budesonide</li>
                    <li>hydrocortisone</li>
                    <li>methylprednisolone</li>
                    <li>prednisone</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Immunomodulators:
                  <ul class="ul2">
                    <li>6-mercaptopurine</li>
                    <li>azathioprine</li>
                    <li>cyclosporine</li>
                    <li>methotrexate</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Biologic therapies:
                  <ul class="ul2">
                    <li>anti-tumor necrosis factor-alpha therapies:
                      <ul class="ul3">
                        <li>adalimumab</li>
                        <li>certolizumab</li>
                        <li>infliximab</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>anti-integrin therapies:
                      <ul class="ul3">
                        <li>natalizumab</li>
                        <li>vedolizumab</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>anti-interleukin-12 and interleukin-23 therapy:
                      <ul class="ul3">
                        <li>ustekinumab</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Other:
                  <ul class="ul2">
                    <li>acetaminophen</li>
                    <li>ibuprofen</li>
                    <li>naproxen</li>
                    <li>aspirin</li>
                    <li>antibiotics</li>
                    <li>loperamide</li>
                    <li>megacolon</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Bowel rest</p>
              <p>Surgery:</p>
              <ul class="ul1">
                <li>Subtotal colectomy</li>
                <li>Proctocolectomy and ileostomy</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Your provider may recommend that you make changes to your diet:</p>
              <ul class="ul1">
                <li>Avoiding carbonated drinks</li>
                <li>Avoiding popcorn, vegetable skins, nuts, and other high-fiber foods</li>
                <li>Drinking more liquids</li>
                <li>Eating smaller meals more often</li>
                <li>Keeping a food diary to help identify foods that cause problem</li>
                <li>Some people also need go on special diet, such as a low-fiber diet.</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </section>
